5.    Process Safety Management Accident Prevention Program

a.    Chlorination Plant:

The chlorination plant at the Facility is subject to OSHA?s Process Safety Management (PSM) regulations for all equipment and operations associated with chlorine storage and the chlorine injection system.  PFI?s PSM program includes the following stringent activities to minimize the potential accidental release:



?    Review of the design of all equipment and controls associated with the chlorine injection system to ensure they are properly designed and installed;

?    Initial safety training and 3-year refresher training for appropriate personnel;

?    Procedures to ensure that all contractors have received safety training prior to operating in or near the chlorine storage area;

?    Periodic inspections of all equipment and controls, with stringent documentation of all inspections;

?    Prompt corrective action for any non-conforming items identified by the regular inspectors;

?    Pre-startup safety reviews are conducted by SEACO prior to system startup, if any equipment or operations are modified;

?    Stringent investigation of any incidents that have a potential to have caused chlorine releases;

?    Periodic evaluation of safety records of all outside contractors who work on the RMP/PSM-regulated system;

?    Development of an effective emergency response program;

?    Implementation of an employee participation program to ensure that all appropriate staff are aware of the PSM program, and are actively consulted regarding safety issues; and

?    Independent audits of the PSM and RMP programs every three years.

b.    Fumigation Operations:

The aluminum phosphide and hydrogen phosphide fumigation operations at the Facility are subject to OSHA?s Process Safety Management (PSM) regulations for all equipment and operations associated with the storage and handling of these compounds.  PFI?s PSM program includes the following stringent act

ivities to minimize the potential accidental release of these compounds:



?    Review of the Fumigation Management Plan prior to any fumigation activities;

?    All fumigation activities are managed by a state certified/licensed pesticide applicator;

?    Only licensed or trained personnel may apply fumigants in accordance with state approved methods and equipment;

?    Safety equipment and protective clothing are utilized for each fumigation activity.

?    Initial safety training and refresher training for appropriate personnel;

?    Procedures to ensure that appropriate personnel have received proper training;

?    Periodic inspections of all equipment and controls, with stringent documentation of all inspections;

?    Prompt corrective action for any non-conforming items identified by the regular inspectors;

?    Safety reviews conducted prior to any fumigation activity;

?    Stringent investigation of any incidents that have a potential to have caused uncontrolled fumigant releases;

?    Periodic evaluation of safety and training records of all personnel who work on the RMP/PSM-regulated system;

?    Development of an effective emergency response program;

?    Implementation of an employee participation program to ensure that all appropriate staff are aware of the PSM program, and are actively consulted regarding safety issues; and

?    Independent audits of the PSM and RMP programs every three years.



6.    Five-Year Accident History

The Facility has not had any releases or near misses involving regulated substances in the past five years that resulted in deaths, injuries, evacuations, sheltering in place, or property damage.



7.    Emergency Response Program

